Intro to R: Analyzing the GWAS Catalog

Peter Carbonetto

February 7, 2017

1 About this document

This is an R Markdown Notebook, or a document (e.g., PDF) generated from an R Markdown Notebook.

R Markdown combines Markdown, a popular, easy-to-read plain text formatting syntax, with “chunks” of R code. R Markdown notebooks can be easily rendered into various formats (PDF, HTML, etc.) for sharing your code and results with collaborators.

This notebook contains code to reproduce some of my analyses of data from the NHGRI-EBI GWAS Catalog. The GWAS Catalog provides results from thousands of genome-wide association studies of inherited diseases and completx traits. My aim in using the GWAS Catalog is to illustrate using R to process and analyze large-scale, complex tabular data.

The GWAS Catalog is “messy” data; hundreds of people have inputted data into the database, with only partial checks on data quality and consistency. In our analyses, we will have to manipulate and filter the data in order to make sense of it.

For background on the GWAS Catalog, see the GWAS Catalog paper. See also the GWAS Diagram for an evocative visual summary of the data.

5 Setting up your R programming environment

There are several options for setting up your R programming environment. In this section, we will explore some of the R environment options that are available on the midway compute cluster and on your laptop. No single option is best for everyone.

5.1 R on your laptop

I recommend installing both R and RStudio.

  1. Install the latest precompiled binary distribution of R by following the instructions on the CRAN website. This provides a text-based R programming environment.

  2. Next, install the free version of RStudio Desktop from here. RStudio provides a complete IDE (integrated development environment) for R programming.

  3. Try running R and RStudio on your computer. You can also try running R from a command-line shell (e.g., iTerm2 on Mac, Cygwin on Windows). To do so, enter into command-line shell software, then simply type R, and hit the enter key.

  4. Test your R graphics setup; e.g., try copying and pasting the code chunk below into R or RStudio. in RStudio, this will (by default) draw the plot in the “Plots” tab. In R, this will render a plot on your screen, but only if you have X Windows software installed on your computer already. For example, for Mac OS X you need to have XQuartz.

library(lattice)
print(xyplot(dist ~ speed,cars,pch = 20,
             cex = 1.5,col = "dodgerblue"))

5.2.4 Running R code without entering the R environment

Although R is mainly used interactively, it is also possible to execute R code like other non-interactive programming languages (e.g., Java). To do this, we use the Rscript command:

Rscript -e "print(head(iris,n = 5))"

More commonly, Rscript is used to execute R code stored in a file; e.g., Rscript my_analysis.R.

9 Installing and loading the packages

In R, a package is a set of functions, data sets, and other materials, that are bundled together. As of this writing, over 10,000 packages have been developed and released. The ease of installing and using packages is one of the reasons R has become so popular. Therefore, it is helpful to understand the steps in installing and loading packages.

Some packages are already available in your environment when you start R. One example is the stats package.

In this workshop, we make use of 3 packages: rmarkdown to render this notebook into another document format; readr to quickly read the GWAS Catalog data; and ggplot2 to visualize the data.

First, check to see if these packages are already installed. If they are not, these commands will report an error:

help(package = rmarkdown)
help(package = readr)
help(package = ggplot2)

If any of the packages are missing, you can install them using the install.packages() function. Even if they are available, I suggest running these commands anyhow to get some practice installing packages. This will also ensure you have the most up-to-date package version.

install.packages("rmarkdown")
install.packages("readr")
install.packages("ggplot2")

There are many ways in which install.packages() will not work; it is difficult to anticipate all the possible errors that can occur. If you are stuck, please ask for help.

Once you have successfully installed the packages, load these packages into your R environment with the library function:

library(rmarkdown)
library(readr)
library(ggplot2)

If you don’t see an error, then the packages were loaded successfully.

11 The R data analysis, step-by-step

Now that we have successfully run the code, we are now ready to walk through the analysis steps in some detail. The simplest way to walk through the code is to copy & paste the individual chunks, or lines of code, into the R console.

11.1 Reading the data into the R environment

The GWAS Catalog data set is a large table with 35,077 rows and 37 columns. It could conceivably be opened in Excel. To illustrate this, open the gwas_catalog_small.xlsx spreadsheet, which contains the first 100 rows of the GWAS Catalog table. Here, we instead read the data into a “data frame” in R. The data frame is R’s standard data structure for storing and working with tables:

library(readr)
gwas <- read_tsv("../data/gwas_catalog.tsv",na = c("","NA","NR"))
Parsed with column specification:
cols(
  .default = col_character(),
  `DATE ADDED TO CATALOG` = col_date(format = ""),
  PUBMEDID = col_integer(),
  DATE = col_date(format = ""),
  UPSTREAM_GENE_ID = col_integer(),
  DOWNSTREAM_GENE_ID = col_integer(),
  UPSTREAM_GENE_DISTANCE = col_integer(),
  DOWNSTREAM_GENE_DISTANCE = col_integer(),
  MERGED = col_integer(),
  SNP_ID_CURRENT = col_integer(),
  INTERGENIC = col_integer(),
  `P-VALUE` = col_double(),
  PVALUE_MLOG = col_double(),
  `OR or BETA` = col_double()
)
See spec(...) for full column specifications.
gwas <- as.data.frame(gwas,stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
print(colnames(gwas))
 [1] "DATE ADDED TO CATALOG"      "PUBMEDID"                  
 [3] "FIRST AUTHOR"               "DATE"

[37] "STUDY ACCESSION"

A lot is going on in this small chunk of code. Here are a few of the many things that are important to know about these few lines of code:

  • We call a function read_tsv that is defined in the readr package. It is a specialized function for quickly reading data tables stored in tab-delimited text format. You can learn more about this function by typing help(read_tsv).

  • We assign the output of this function to a variable called gwas. This creates a new variable in our working environment. Type ls() to get the list of variables in the current environment.

  • Since the output from read_tsv is not a data frame, and we would like to work with a data frame, we convert it to a data frame using the as.data.frame function. By default, this function automatically converts “strings” (text) to “factors” (categorical variables), which we don’t want (one of the many annoying default behaviours of R), so we set stringsAsFactors = FALSE.

  • The third line accesses a property of the data frame, the names of the columns.

11.3 Manipulating the data

R has a wide range of tools specifically aimed at manipulating data frames. Here we will get a small sampling of R’s capabilities.

We certainly don’t have time to look closely at all the GWAS Catalog data. But we can at least start by looking closely at the “MAPPED_TRAIT” column, which records the relevant disease or trait:

# Typically, the "summary" function is useful. However, our first attempt at 
# summarizing the MAPPED_TRAIT column doesn't yield much useful information
x <- gwas[["MAPPED_TRAIT"]]
print(summary(x))
   Length     Class      Mode 
    35077 character character 
# What if we convert the column to a categorical variable? That helps,
# but not a lot; there are too many categories, or "levels", for the summary
# to be useful. (I capped the summary at the top 10 most frequently occurring 
# traits, otherwise it will be a very long list.)
trait <- factor(x)
print(nlevels(trait))
[1] 1539
print(summary(trait,maxsum = 10))
                                       response to bronchodilator, FEV/FEC ratio 
                                                                            1631 
                            forced expiratory volume, response to bronchodilator 
                                                                            1182 
                                                                 body mass index 
                                                                             922 
                                                                   schizophrenia 
                                                                             906 
                                                                     body height 
                                                                             866 
                                             serum IgG glycosylation measurement 
                                                                             699 
response to bronchodilator, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, FEV/FEC ratio 
                                                                             473 
                                                       type II diabetes mellitus 
                                                                             411 
                                                                 Crohn's disease 
                                                                             393 
                                                                         (Other) 
                                                                           27594 
# To make our initial investigation more manageable, let's focus on
# only traits that appear at least 100 times in the database. This is an 
# arbitrary cutoff of course, but data analysis is best approached in 
# small bites.
counts         <- table(trait)
traits.to.keep <- names(which(counts >= 100))
cat("Number of traits after filtering step:",length(traits.to.keep),"\n")
Number of traits after filtering step: 56 
gwas.small <- subset(gwas,is.element(MAPPED_TRAIT,traits.to.keep))
cat("Number of table rows before filtering step:",nrow(gwas))
Number of table rows before filtering step: 35077
cat("Number of table rows after filtering step:",nrow(gwas.small))
Number of table rows after filtering step: 16375
# Now that MAPPED_TRAIT in the gwas.small data frame has a smaller
# number of categories (levels), let's convert that column to a 
# factor.
gwas.small$MAPPED_TRAIT <- factor(gwas.small$MAPPED_TRAIT)

This code chunk illustrated two manipulations of the data: (1) we filtered out columns that didn’t meet our criteria; (2) we converted one column two a more convenient data type.

A few more comments about this code chunk:

  • The summary function is a generic function that can be used for many different variables and data types. You will find it useful in many situations.

  • A factor is the term that R uses for “categorical variable”. It is one of the standard data types, and it is again useful in many different situations.

  • The table command (a confusing name, admittedly) is used to count categorical data (factors).

  • The call to the subset function creates a new data table with only entries in which the MAPPED_TRAIT column is one of the selected traits. We have saved the output to a new variable, gwas.small. We now have two data frames in our working environment: gwas and gwas.small.

  • The last line in the chunk converts the column to a factor data type. This will be useful in the next section for quickly creating data summaries.

  • Note that the conversion to factor will not taken effect unless we assign the output of the factor function back to the column contained in the gwas.small data frame.

For the remainder, we will work with gwas.small only.

That’s not bad, but a figure is usually effective than a table for gaining insight into the data. Let’s create a figure using the ggplot2 package. ggplot has emerged as the most widely used approach for plotting in R because it is powerful and easy to use (after getting a hang of the admittedly unconventional interface).

Let’s first create the plot, and then we will try to understand what the code is doing.

library(ggplot2)
print(ggplot(gwas.small,aes(MAPPED_TRAIT)) +
  geom_bar(fill = "darkorange",width = 0.5) + 
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0,2000,250)) +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(panel.grid.major.y = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor.y = element_blank()))

It is difficult to understand how ggplot works with one example. If this your first exposure to ggplot, here is what I suggest you take away from this example:

  • It is most natural to use ggplot with data frames; the aes function tells ggplot which columns of the data frame to visualize. For a bar chart, there is only one variable to visualize, so we only list one column, aes(MAPPED_TRAIT).

  • After the geom_bar call, the rest of the function calls adjust the properties of the figure, and aren’t necessary.

Followup exercise 1: Try removing and re-including the lines after the call to geom_bar() to see what effect these lines have on the plot. Make sure to remove the last plus sign from your code otherwise R will report a parsing error. Also refer to the online ggplot reference.

Followup exercise 2: Use the reorder function to manipulate the MAPPED_TRAIT column in the gwas.small data frame, then use this data frame to create a new bar plot in which the traits are listed in increasing or decreasing order by the number of associations.

11.5 Defining a function to efficiently reuse code

So far, we have focused on getting broad-level summaries of the GWAS Catalog data. In this final portion of our data analysis, we want to create plots that yield more detailed understanding of individual traits. I would like to create the same type of plot that could be applied to multiple traits without having to rewrite same or similar code to generate each plot.

A key concept in R is that we can define a variable in our environment that is a function. We will call this function trait_scatterplot:

trait_scatterplot <- function (trait, max.pvalue) {

  # Colours and symbols I like using.
  clrs   <- rep(c("darkorange","dodgerblue","forestgreen","red","navyblue",
                  "gold","yellowgreen","darkviolet","magenta","cyan"),
                times = 4)
  shapes <- rep(c(20,1,2,4),each = 10)

  # Change the "P-VALUE"" column to "PVALUE".
  i <- which(colnames(gwas.small) == "P-VALUE")
  colnames(gwas.small)[i] <- "PVALUE"
  
  # Extract the rows we are interested in.
  x <- subset(gwas.small,
              MAPPED_TRAIT == trait &
              as.numeric(PVALUE) < max.pvalue)

  # Extract the columns we are interested in: the effect size ("odds ratio or 
  # beta"), the frequency of the risk allele, the study id, and a label
  # indicating whether the association maps to HLA genes.
  x <- data.frame(
         effect.size = x[["OR or BETA"]],
         allele.freq = log10(as.numeric(x[["RISK ALLELE FREQUENCY"]])),
         study       = factor(x[["STUDY ACCESSION"]]),
         hla         = factor(grepl("HLA",x[["REPORTED GENE(S)"]]),
                              levels = c(FALSE,TRUE),labels = c("","HLA")))
  
  # The function's return value is a ggplot object. 
  return(ggplot(x,aes(x     = effect.size,
                      y     = allele.freq,
                      color = study,
                      shape = study,
                      label = hla)) +
    geom_point(size = 2) + 
    geom_text(size = 2.5,hjust = "left",vjust = "top",col = "black") + 
    scale_color_manual(values = clrs) +
    scale_shape_manual(values = shapes) +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
          panel.grid.minor = element_blank()))
}
print(trait_scatterplot(trait = "Crohn's disease",max.pvalue = 1e-12))

print(trait_scatterplot(trait = "multiple sclerosis",max.pvalue = 1e-8))

print(trait_scatterplot(trait = "schizophrenia",max.pvalue = 1e-10))
